Resolve establishing the Harmony commission to study and make recommendations related to
the welfare and best interests of children in care and protection cases.
1 Resolved, there shall be a Harmony Commission, to study, examine and make
2 recommendations regarding the welfare and best interest considerations of children in care and
3 protection cases and petitions to dispense with consent cases conducted pursuant to section 29C
4 of chapter 119 of the General Laws and section 3 of chapter 210 of the General Laws.
5 The commission shall consist of: the child advocate or a designee, who shall serve as co-
6 chair; 1 member of the Massachusetts Bar Association, who shall be a former first justice, who
7 shall serve as co-chair; the chairs of the joint committee on children, families and persons with
8 disabilities, who shall serve as co-chairs; the chairs of the joint committee on the judiciary; the
9 chair and vice-chair of the Massachusetts Black and Latino Legislative Caucus or their
10 designees; 5 members to be appointed by the governor, 2 of whom shall have been in foster care
11 as children and 2 of whom shall be foster parents; the attorney general or a designee; the
12 commissioner of children and families or a designee; the chief counsel of the committee for
13 public counsel services or a designee; 1 member to be appointed by the committee for public
14 counsel services who shall be an attorney certified by the children and family law division of the
1 of 4

15 committee for public counsel services who shall have a minimum of 7 years of experience in
16 care and protection cases, represents both children and parents and has completed not less than 5
17 permanent custody or petition-to-dispense trials; 2 members appointed by the Massachusetts Bar
18 Association, who shall be former judges who have preferably retired not more than 5 years prior
19 to their appointment, who have not less than 7 years of service on the juvenile court and are from
20 geographically-diverse juvenile court districts and 1 of whom shall be a former first justice; the
21 commissioner of probation or a designee; 1 member appointed by the Massachusetts Court
22 Appointed Special Advocates, Inc. who shall have a minimum of 5 years of experience with the
23 advocates, including supervisory experience; 1 member appointed by the Massachusetts Alliance
24 of Juvenile Court Clinics who shall be a clinician representative from the court clinic of the
25 juvenile court department; the deputy court administrator for the juvenile court or a designee; 1
26 member to be appointed by the Massachusetts Commission on LGBTQ Youth; 1 member to be
27 appointed by Jane Doe, Inc.: The Massachusetts Coalition Against Sexual Assault and Domestic
28 Violence; 1 member to be appointed by the Disability Law Center, Inc.; 1 member to be
29 appointed by the Massachusetts Association of Guardians ad Litem; 1 member to be appointed
30 by the Massachusetts Child Welfare Coalition who shall be an attorney; and 1 member to be
31 appointed by the National Association of Counsel for Children. All appointments shall be made
32 not later than 30 days after the effective date of this resolve. Members of the commission shall
33 serve without compensation.
34 The commission shall study how a child’s rights, welfare and best interest considerations
35 are currently handled in care and protection cases and petition to dispense with consent cases and
36 make recommendations for how to better protect and serve children in such cases. The study
37 shall include, but not be limited to: (i) a review of constitutional provisions, statutes, interstate
2 of 4

38 compacts, case law, executive orders, rules of court and standing orders, state agency and
39 judicial rules and regulations, intergovernmental or multi-state memoranda of understanding and
40 state agency and judicial policies, procedures, practices and trainings; (ii) an examination of how
41 care and protection cases and petition to dispense with consent cases disproportionately impact
42 children of color, immigrant children, children with disabilities, lesbian, gay, bisexual,
43 transgender and queer children, children who have experienced trauma and children living in
44 poverty; (iii) an analysis of ways to ensure the constitutional rights of parents and children while
45 prioritizing the well being and safety of children, including the children’s best interest, safety and
46 well being while in the care or custody of the department of children and families; and (iv) a
47 study of sibling visitation rights.
48 The commission shall base its study on reports from the Massachusetts Trial Court
49 Permanency Core Working Group to further investigate recommendations or ensure
50 implementation of recommendations.
51 The commission shall hold public hearings and solicit public comment not less than 3
52 times prior to the filing of its report. The hearings shall be held in geographically-diverse areas
53 and at least 1 public hearing shall be held after the issuance of a draft report, which shall include
54 any recommendations and draft legislation to implement the recommendations. Interested parties
55 shall have the opportunity to be heard at the public hearings and submit written testimony or
56 comments. The commission shall be subject to the open meeting law under sections 18 to 25,
57 inclusive, of chapter 30A of the General Laws. The commission shall hold its first meeting not
58 later than 60 days after the effective date of this resolve. The commission shall meet not less than
59 monthly.
3 of 4

60 Not later than January 1, 2026, the commission shall file a report of its findings and
61 recommendations, including racial impact statements regarding any of its recommendations, with
62 the clerks of the senate and the house of representatives, the governor and the chief justice of the
63 juvenile court department. The report shall be publicly posted on the website of the department
64 of children and families.
